api_list.name: properties/get-parcel-bounds
api_list.description: Get parcel bounds info. This endpoint is used to get fipsCode and apn to pass in .../properties/get-flood-info endpoint.

required_parameters.name: propertyId
required_parameters.description: The value of propertyId field returned in .../properties/list endpoint.

api_list.name: properties/list
api_list.description: List properties for sales, sold, etc... with options and filters

required_parameters.name: region_type
required_parameters.description:
One of the following : -1:Unknowns|1:Neighborhood|2:Zip Code|4:State|5:County|6:City|7:School|8:School District|9:Service Region|10:Minor Civil Division|11:Country|30:CA Postal Code|31:CA Province|32:CA Provincial Division|33:CA Municipality|34:CA Forward Sortation Area
You need to use regex to examine the value of url field returned in .../auto-complete for suitable value. Ex : '/city/30749/...', it is city so it is 6 in this case.

required_parameters.name: region_id
required_parameters.description: You need to use regex to extract the value of id field returned in .../auto-complete endpoint. Ex : '2_30749', 30749 is the value you need to extract from the string.

required_parameters.name: uipt
required_parameters.description:
Property types, uses of the following : 1-Home|2-Condo|3-Townhouse|4-Multi-family|5-Land|6-Other|7-Manufactured|8-Co-op
Separated by comma for multiple options. Ex : 1,2,3,4,7,8

required_parameters.name: status
required_parameters.description: One of the following : 1-Active listings|8-Coming soon listings|9-Active + coming soon listings|130-Only under contract/pending|131-Active + under contract/pending

optional_parameters.name: financing_type
optional_parameters.description: Accepted Financing, one of the following : 1-FHA|2-VA

optional_parameters.name: time_on_market_range
optional_parameters.description:
Time on Redfin, you need to put the minus before/after every numbers. Ex :
1-:Less than 1 day|3-:Less than 3 days|7-|14-|30-|-30:More than 30 days|-60|-120|-:For any time

optional_parameters.name: pool_types
optional_parameters.description: One of the following : 1-Private pool|2-Community pool|3-Private or Community pool|4-No private pool

optional_parameters.name: primary_bed_on_main
optional_parameters.description: true : has primary bedroom on main floor

optional_parameters.name: unrated_schools
optional_parameters.description: true : Include unrated schools. Use along with school_rating parameter.

optional_parameters.name: walk_score
optional_parameters.description: Filter by walk score, you need to put the minus after every numbers. Ex : 10-|20-|30-|etc...

optional_parameters.name: school_rating
optional_parameters.description: Filter by school rate, you need to put the minus after every numbers. Ex : 1-|2-|3-|...|10-

optional_parameters.name: transit_score
optional_parameters.description: Filter by transit score, you need to put the minus after every numbers. Ex : 10-|20-|30-|etc...

optional_parameters.name: bike_score
optional_parameters.description: Filter by bike score, you need to put the minus after every numbers. Ex : 10-|20-|30-|etc...

optional_parameters.name: basement_types
optional_parameters.description: One of the following : 1-Finished|3-Unfinished. Separated by comma for multiple options. Ex : 1,3

optional_parameters.name: school_types
optional_parameters.description: Use along with school_rating parameter. One of the following : 1-Elementary schools|2-Middle schools|3-High schools. Separated by comma for multiple options. Ex : 1,2,3

optional_parameters.name: num_beds
optional_parameters.description: Filter by number of beds room at least. Ex : 2

optional_parameters.name: sold_within_days
optional_parameters.description: Use this parameter to list SOLD properties. If you pass this parameter, leave sf parameter empty.

optional_parameters.name: rd
optional_parameters.description:
Price reduce, you need to put the minus before/after every numbers. Ex :
1-:Less than 1 day|3-:Less than 3 days|7-|14-|30-|-30:More than 30 days|-60|-120|-:For any time

optional_parameters.name: sf
optional_parameters.description:
MLS listings, uses of the following : 1,7-Agent listed Homes|2-MLS listed foreclosures|3-For sale by owner|4-Foreclosures|5,6-New construction
Separated by comma for multiple options. Ex : 1,2,3,5,6,7

optional_parameters.name: pkg
optional_parameters.description: Garage spots 1-|2-|3-|4-|5- (You need to put the minus behind every numbers)

optional_parameters.name: num_baths
optional_parameters.description: Filter by number of baths at least. Ex : 2.5

optional_parameters.name: num_homes
optional_parameters.description: Number of items per response (Max 400). Redfin always return max 400 properties for every search, there is no paging feature.

schoolReviews.review: I did not have a good experience. Communication to parents is terrible. This year they combined PS 100 or something and was not aware until the 1st day of school. These teachers sound so overwhelmed. Canâ€™t even remember a conversation they held with a specific child. Definitely do not recommend this school.
My name as injured twice in this school.. The education is zero. The stuff are rude and unfriendly . I transferred my son to a different school. Parents be careful with your choice.

Great teachers what are working hard with our childrens. My daughter was in this school, and in the first time I helped her with homework, after than I have no problems with her. She took a good results! Thank you!
Rude teachers that cann't control their temper and curse and scream at kids. Terrible main office, dirty corridors and bathrooms.

My two kids go here sevrl years and I cant believe the bad comments on this website. Principal, Teahcres, Dean and AP's all take care of kids here. You can even see AP's and Dean outside walking our blocks before school to get kids in safe and on time!
It is most caring schools ever. They always helping my children. Thanks god my kids go here!

I am a former student here in PS 225. Most of the teachers don't give much respect to the 8th graders, while a handful are absolute gems. My friend went to this school with me and she was barely able to speak English. She once got lost on her way down to lunch. A teacher saw her and my friend was screamed at by the teacher until my friend was reduced to tears. Bullying is not taken seriously here. I was a bullying victim and how was the situation "taken care of"? A talk with the assistant principal. Other than that, no serious punishments were carried out. The building's 4th floor is also home to PS 771, making manners even worse for the students AND the staff. If bullying occurs in lower/elementary grade(s), do NOT take this lightly because in middle school the issue has a very high chance of escalating to violence, even on school grounds! Do not send your kid here unless he/she has physical strength and a quick wit.

schoolGranularRatings.schoolGranularRatingCopyText: Students at this school are making average academic progress from one grade to the next compared to similar students in the state.
schoolGranularRatings.schoolGranularRatingsDescription: The Student Progress Rating measures whether students at this school are making academic progress over time based on student growth data provided by the Department of Education. Specifically, this rating looks at how much progress individual students have made on state assessments during the past year or more, how this performance aligns with expected progress based on a student growth model established by the state Department of Education, and how this school's growth data compares to other schools in the state. The Growth Rating was created using 2019 Student growth data from New York State Education Department.

schoolGranularRatings.schoolGranularRatingCopyText:

Because state averages can be low, some students at this school may still not be performing at grade level.

schoolReviews.review: I attended Lincoln from 2003-2007 and was in the IPS program. For the most part this program was a pleasant experience. The teachers were dedicated to their jobs, the courses were challenging, and it prepared us for college. However, the non-honors programs in the school are very poor. Security was always an issue, and students were free to roam the halls with little consequence. My advise is that if you're attending the IPS or honors program, you will be pleased with the quality of education. Otherwise, I would look elsewhere.

For the person who wrote a review regarding their attendance 60 YEARS AGO, a lot has CHANGED!!! You should make a visit. The school is notorious for kids being bullied, and security arriving way too late, and if they don't get you in school they will get you after school. There must be a change this has been going on for years!!!! Kids are bused from other locations, and sometime not the best neighborhoods, to ensure the school is integrated, and this does have an affect to population and to those who live in the area.

This school is so terrible they only focus on the football and basket ball teams not subjects or new books or anything of that sort. The teachers are very unexperienced and have no control over the classroom. The kids there are ruthless fights all the time as well as bullying. The only thing is good is the teams and vet. Course. But overall this school is terrible . Even from my own experience when I used to go there a lot of kids used to pick on me and try to hurt me . My teachers even new about this but yet had no control. One day I was driven out the classroom but them and left the school while no one stopped me not even the teachers or deans or security I just walked out crying. This school only focuses on sport teams and being on the news about it. Nothing more. Really a disappointment.
I went to Lincoln 60 years ago. Lived across the street from it. Love it then used to go to the pool for 3 cents a day . That was in the 1940's Went to school 1952 1956 I loved it.
I really love this school my daughter is about to graduate with high honors at the school the teachers are amazing

Lincoln is not a 'great' school but it's not a terrible school either.Some teachers seem more concerned/supportive than others but that is in any school. You will get out of Lincoln what you put in. If you want to half a-- your way through high school then that's on you. It is not a school that revolves around the underachievers.

This school is really notorious. I currently attend the school, and think that it is looked down on from a blind perspective. If you try, you will learn as much as you please. If you don't, you wont. The school, in a way, successfully separates students based on their averages by the application of two programs : IPS and Gilder Lehrman. The students who are known to be violent are therefore in a whole different world than you, so violence is out of the question. This school, because of the high number of students with low averages, has to focus on the failings kids instead of the ones who attain a 90-100 average. There are therefore only about 6 AP classes, and 5-6 college now (Which isn't that bad) Don't be fooled, thought, because if you have a good GPA, you will get an enormous amount of extra classes.

schoolReviews.review: The best school we had so far. My son was on the remote kindergarten last year. He learned very well. We had a super awesome teacher Mrs Santiago and a coolest principal Ms Speroni. Everyone in school are very helpful. Ms Mariya , Ms Gina, Ms Cheryl and so on. We are so proud to be part of this school. Unfortunately, we moved to other state now. We will miss you all.

The best school ever! My son is 4 grade student. I transferred from PS 100 last year. Very professional teachers and wise and strong leadership! The principal of the school Madam Lisa Speroni every morning outside meets all students and their parents with a smile and charges everyone with positive energy! PS 253 has been recognized as a National Blue Ribbon School for 2019! I would like to express my gratitude to all stuff of the school for appropriate support and good learning environment for our kids.

My child is in Kindergarden at this school. I would say that the gem of this school is Ms Mastropierro. She is an AMAZING teacher, so experienced, caring and kind. The atmosphere that she creates in class makes the children love school and thrive. The parent-teacher coordinator Ms Gina is very approachable and friendly. The school is clean and it seems like the staff is kind, open, and friendly (with the exception of security guards who are often very rude) However, the reading requirement that are pushed and the amount of testing done in Kindergarden is INAPPROPRIATE for children of this age group. The constant testing creates unnecessary amount of stress for five year old children, especially for the English language learners that make up about 1/3 of our class. I also feel that not enough time is dedicated to the arts. Otherwise, its a very nice neighborhood school.

The principal of P.S. 253, the parent coordinator, the faculty and staff are absolutely amazing!! It is obvious in everything they do, that the children come first. It is an environment that I am proud to send my daughter to and I am extremely pleased with the nurturing and care displayed by the principal and her staff. This school is a gem!!

I am proud to be a graduate of this public school, which was many years ago. I came from a big family and had recently immigrated to United States. We came here with just our clothes on our backs. My experience at P.S. was tough but I took alot away from that. One specific teacher Mrs. Beatrice, who taught 5th graders, made a big difference in my life. She enlisted in me the importance of self confidence and that you can do anything if you put your mind to it. Though they were not her exact words but it was hers actions and continous attention to each student as an individual that I still remember to this day. From that point I went onto graduate high school, complete my bachelor's degree, and then entered medical school. I completed my residency and am currently an emergency medicine physician. Thank you Mrs. Beatrice, where ever you are!!

schoolReviews.review: Both of my children attend Mazel Day School. They started in Pre-Nursery and now the oldest is in 1st grade. great environment for kids to learn and grow. Love the progressive education approach. Staff and teachers to always attentive to any concerns and often helped me with parenting troubles.

I have been a parent at Mazel for over 5 years. My older child graduated from Mazel middle school and is doing well in HS. My younger child is in the 4th grade. Prior to Mazel, both kids attended various public schools in Brooklyn and Long Island. Mazel has been able to offer my kids stimulating, progressive environment as well as warm, caring atmosphere infused with Jewish values and heritage. Jews from all walks of life are welcome here, observant or not and no one is made feel inferior. The administration at Mazel welcomes parental involvement and feedback.

Mazel Day school is the premier Jewish day school in the South Brooklyn Area. They provide a top notch education in both scholastic and Judaic studies. Mazel caters to their community by providing Russian language education.

This school is amazing. We have been part of this beautiful community for close to six years now and I can't say enough about the quality of staff, quality of education, attention and care provided to our kids, and every single aspect of the school environment. Children are happy and excited to go to school every day - it doesn't happen often, especially in schools of NYC.

schoolReviews.review: terrbile place to be, transfer out when you can

I was a freshman student of 2011. This school is horrendous pertaining to both academics/enviorment. I definetly will not reccomend this school to any student. Academics are not challenging and this school does not prepare you for college. I transferred as a freshman to a much better high school. I left grady with a 99 average with absolutely no studying. This school is horrible horrible, i hated this school so much the bullying, the gangs, violence.

I graduated from Grady in 1989 as a marginal student in the electrical installations program. I've gone on to be very happy with where I am today. I went on to earn a masters degree and currently work in state government. I have to agree with others who have stated school is what you make it. I'm pleased to see Grady still offers a wide variety of programs. I don't think people realize how important vocational and technical schools are, especially in today's world. Students who are smart enough to take advantage of the programs Grady has to offer will be well positioned for future success. The shortage of skilled labor and trained technicians is well documented. Every city should have a few schools like Grady. What I learned in Grady has served me well in everyday life. The confidence I have in working with my hands to build and fix things came from my vocational experience. It is also where I was first challenged to problem solve in a real way. Even though I didn't apply myself as I should have while in school, my diploma from Grady gave me many options. I am proud of my degrees, but they are truly no better than a solid vocational/technical education.

This school lacks good administrative and competency. The students sneak out of the school at their own will. I have two boys in Grady, One graduating this year and the other going to the eleventh grade. I always said, it's not what the schools about, it's what you make out of it.

This school provides the necessary tools for a child to excell beyond H.S. Many parents complain about how the school is ran but few show up to pta meetings. this school is going places if you have a problem with it choose from the many other schools that are being closed down. as a former student i have exceeded past my own expectations.

schoolReviews.review: I attended Lincoln from 2003-2007 and was in the IPS program. For the most part this program was a pleasant experience. The teachers were dedicated to their jobs, the courses were challenging, and it prepared us for college. However, the non-honors programs in the school are very poor. Security was always an issue, and students were free to roam the halls with little consequence. My advise is that if you're attending the IPS or honors program, you will be pleased with the quality of education. Otherwise, I would look elsewhere.

For the person who wrote a review regarding their attendance 60 YEARS AGO, a lot has CHANGED!!! You should make a visit. The school is notorious for kids being bullied, and security arriving way too late, and if they don't get you in school they will get you after school. There must be a change this has been going on for years!!!! Kids are bused from other locations, and sometime not the best neighborhoods, to ensure the school is integrated, and this does have an affect to population and to those who live in the area.

This school is so terrible they only focus on the football and basket ball teams not subjects or new books or anything of that sort. The teachers are very unexperienced and have no control over the classroom. The kids there are ruthless fights all the time as well as bullying. The only thing is good is the teams and vet. Course. But overall this school is terrible . Even from my own experience when I used to go there a lot of kids used to pick on me and try to hurt me . My teachers even new about this but yet had no control. One day I was driven out the classroom but them and left the school while no one stopped me not even the teachers or deans or security I just walked out crying. This school only focuses on sport teams and being on the news about it. Nothing more. Really a disappointment.
I went to Lincoln 60 years ago. Lived across the street from it. Love it then used to go to the pool for 3 cents a day . That was in the 1940's Went to school 1952 1956 I loved it.
I really love this school my daughter is about to graduate with high honors at the school the teachers are amazing

Lincoln is not a 'great' school but it's not a terrible school either.Some teachers seem more concerned/supportive than others but that is in any school. You will get out of Lincoln what you put in. If you want to half a-- your way through high school then that's on you. It is not a school that revolves around the underachievers.

This school is really notorious. I currently attend the school, and think that it is looked down on from a blind perspective. If you try, you will learn as much as you please. If you don't, you wont. The school, in a way, successfully separates students based on their averages by the application of two programs : IPS and Gilder Lehrman. The students who are known to be violent are therefore in a whole different world than you, so violence is out of the question. This school, because of the high number of students with low averages, has to focus on the failings kids instead of the ones who attain a 90-100 average. There are therefore only about 6 AP classes, and 5-6 college now (Which isn't that bad) Don't be fooled, thought, because if you have a good GPA, you will get an enormous amount of extra classes.

schoolReviews.review: Both of my children attend Mazel Day School. They started in Pre-Nursery and now the oldest is in 1st grade. great environment for kids to learn and grow. Love the progressive education approach. Staff and teachers to always attentive to any concerns and often helped me with parenting troubles.
My daughter attends grade k. She is very happy and so am I. Caring atmosphere, rigorous curriculum and a sense of community is what makes Mazel very special. I highly recommend it.

I have been a parent at Mazel for over 5 years. My older child graduated from Mazel middle school and is doing well in HS. My younger child is in the 4th grade. Prior to Mazel, both kids attended various public schools in Brooklyn and Long Island. Mazel has been able to offer my kids stimulating, progressive environment as well as warm, caring atmosphere infused with Jewish values and heritage. Jews from all walks of life are welcome here, observant or not and no one is made feel inferior. The administration at Mazel welcomes parental involvement and feedback.

Mazel Day school is the premier Jewish day school in the South Brooklyn Area. They provide a top notch education in both scholastic and Judaic studies. Mazel caters to their community by providing Russian language education.

This school is amazing. We have been part of this beautiful community for close to six years now and I can't say enough about the quality of staff, quality of education, attention and care provided to our kids, and every single aspect of the school environment. Strong general studies, fluency in 3 languages (kids read and write in English, Hebrew, and Russian), rich Judaic studies component, various extracurricular activities (during the school day as well as on premises after school), caring staff that knows every child by name, and knows every single family in the school, and most importantly amazing children that come from truly outstanding families. Children are happy and excited to go to school every day - it doesn't happen often, especially in schools of NYC.

I had my son in Mazel for several years now and my second child will join him next year. The school had been an excellent experience for the whole family and I seen my child blossom academically and in character. He is advanced in math and science and the school had worked closely with him to provide him enrichment work to continue to challenge himself, while working with him on strengthening his academic weaknesses. As importantly he is growing up to be a respectful and confident young man all due to the character traits that are taught and emphasized in school.
Great school in every aspect. Warm environment, excellent curriculum, amazing staff. Teaches kids to be self sufficient and capable while instilling great values. We couldn't be happier!
